# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: xenomai
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] In computing, **interrupt latency** refers to the delay between the start of an Interrupt Request (IRQ) and the start of the respective Interrupt Service Routine (ISR).
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] For many operating systems, devices are serviced as soon as the device's interrupt handler is executed.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Interrupt latency may be affected by microprocessor design, interrupt controllers, interrupt masking, and the operating system's (OS) interrupt handling methods.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] There is usually a trade-off between interrupt latency, throughput, and processor utilization.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Many of the techniques of CPU and OS design that improve interrupt latency will decrease throughput and increase processor utilization.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Techniques that increase throughput may increase interrupt latency and increase processor utilization.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Lastly, trying to reduce processor utilization may increase interrupt latency and decrease throughput.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Minimum interrupt latency is largely determined by the interrupt controller circuit and its configuration.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] They can also affect the jitter in the interrupt latency, which can drastically affect the real-time schedulability of the system.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] The Intel APIC architecture is well known for producing a huge amount of interrupt latency jitter.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Maximum interrupt latency is largely determined by the methods an OS uses for interrupt handling.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] For example, most processors allow programs to disable interrupts, putting off the execution of interrupt handlers, in order to protect critical sections of code.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] During the execution of such a critical section, all interrupt handlers that cannot execute safely within a critical section are blocked (they save the minimum amount of information required to restart the interrupt handler after all critical sections have exited).
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] So the interrupt latency for a blocked interrupt is extended to the end of the critical section, plus any interrupts with equal and higher priority that arrived while the block was in place.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Many computer systems require low interrupt latencies, especially embedded systems that need to control machinery in real-time.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Sometimes these systems use a real-time operating system (RTOS).
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] An RTOS makes the promise that no more than a specified maximum amount of time will pass between executions of subroutines.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] In order to do this, the RTOS must also guarantee that interrupt latency will never exceed a predefined maximum.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Advanced interrupt controllers implement a multitude of hardware features in order to minimize the overhead during context switches and the effective interrupt latency.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Also, there are many other methods hardware may use to help lower the requirements for shorter interrupt latency in order to make a given interrupt latency tolerable in a situation.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] These include buffers, and flow control.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] For example, most network cards implement transmit and receive ring buffers, interrupt rate limiting, and hardware flow control.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Buffers allow data to be stored until it can be transferred, and flow control allows the network card to pause communications without having to discard data if the buffer is full.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Modern hardware also implements interrupt rate limiting.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] This helps prevent interrupt storms or live-locks by having the hardware wait a programmable minimum amount of time between each interrupt it generates.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Interrupt rate limiting reduces the amount of time spent servicing interrupts, allowing the processor to spend more time doing useful work.
[src:xenomai/interrupt-latency] Exceeding this time results in a soft (recoverable) or hard (non-recoverable) error.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A **kernel** is a computer program at the core of a computer's operating system that always has complete control over everything in the system.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is also responsible for preventing and mitigating conflicts between different processes.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] It is the portion of the operating system that is always resident in memory and facilitates interactions between hardware and software components.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A full kernel controls all hardware resources (e.g.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] I/O, memory, cryptography) via device drivers, arbitrates conflicts between processes concerning such resources, and optimizes the use of common resources, such as CPU, cache, file systems, and network sockets.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] On most systems, the kernel is one of the first programs loaded on startup (after the bootloader).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] It handles the rest of startup as well as memory, peripherals, and input/output (I/O) requests from software, translating them into data-processing instructions for the central processing unit.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The critical code of the kernel is usually loaded into a separate area of memory, which is protected from access by application software or other less critical parts of the operating system.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel performs its tasks, such as scheduling processes, managing hardware devices such as the hard disk, and handling interrupts, in this protected kernel space.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In contrast, application programs such as browsers, word processors, or audio or video players use a separate area of memory, user space.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This prevents user data and kernel data from interfering with each other and causing instability and slowness, as well as preventing malfunctioning applications from affecting other applications or crashing the entire operating system.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Even in systems where the kernel is included in application address spaces, memory protection is used to prevent unauthorized applications from modifying the kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel's interface is a low-level abstraction layer.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a process requests a service from the kernel, it must invoke a system call, usually through a wrapper function.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] There are different kernel architecture designs.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels run entirely in a single address space with the CPU executing in supervisor mode, mainly for speed.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels run most but not all of their services in user space, like user processes do, mainly for resilience and modularity.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] MINIX 3 is a notable example of microkernel design.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some kernels, such as the Linux kernel, are both monolithic and modular, since they can insert and remove loadable kernel modules at runtime.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This central component of a computer system is responsible for executing programs.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel takes responsibility for deciding at any time which of the many running programs should be allocated to the processor or processors.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Random-access memory (RAM) is used to store both program instructions and data.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Typically, both need to be present in memory for a program to execute.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often, multiple programs will want memory access, frequently demanding more memory than the computer has available.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is responsible for deciding which memory each process can use, and determining what to do when insufficient memory is available.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] I/O devices include, but are not limited to, peripherals such as keyboards, mice, disk drives, printers, USB devices, network adapters, and display devices.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel provides convenient methods for applications to use these devices, which are typically abstracted by the kernel so that applications do not need to know their implementation details.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Key aspects necessary in resource management are defining the execution domain (address space) and the protection mechanism used to mediate access to the resources within a domain.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Kernels also provide methods for synchronization and inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] These implementations may be located within the kernel itself or the kernel can also rely on other processes it is running.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Although the kernel must provide IPC in order to provide access to the facilities provided by each other, kernels must also provide running programs with a method to make requests to access these facilities.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is also responsible for context switching between processes or threads.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel has full access to the system's memory and must allow processes to safely access this memory as they require it.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often the first step in doing this is virtual addressing, usually achieved by paging and/or segmentation.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual addressing allows the kernel to make a given physical address appear to be another address, the virtual address.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual address spaces may be different for different processes; the memory that one process accesses at a particular (virtual) address may be different memory from what another process accesses at the same address.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This allows every program to behave as if it is the only one (apart from the kernel) running and thus prevents applications from crashing each other.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] On many systems, a program's virtual address may refer to data that is not currently in memory.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The layer of indirection provided by virtual addressing allows the operating system to use other data stores, like a hard drive, to store what would otherwise have to remain in main memory (RAM).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] As a result, operating systems can allow programs to use more memory than the system has physically available.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a program needs data that is not currently in RAM, the CPU signals to the kernel that this has happened, and the kernel responds by writing the contents of an inactive memory block to disk (if necessary) and replacing it with the data requested by the program.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The program can then be resumed from the point where it was stopped.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This scheme is generally known as demand paging.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual addressing also allows creation of virtual partitions of memory in two disjoint areas, one being reserved for the kernel (kernel space) and the other for the applications (user space).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The applications are not permitted by the processor to address kernel memory, thus preventing an application from damaging the running kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This fundamental partition of memory space has contributed much to the current designs of actual general-purpose kernels and is almost universal in such systems, although some research kernels (e.g., Singularity) take other approaches.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] To perform useful functions, processes need access to the peripherals connected to the computer, which are controlled by the kernel through device drivers.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A device driver is a computer program encapsulating, monitoring and controlling a hardware device (via its hardware/software interface (HSI)) on behalf of the OS.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] It provides the operating system with an API, procedures and information about how to control and communicate with a certain piece of hardware.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Device drivers are an important and vital dependency for all OS and their applications.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The design goal of a driver is abstraction; the function of the driver is to translate the OS-mandated abstract function calls (programming calls) into device-specific calls.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In theory, a device should work correctly with a suitable driver.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Device drivers are used for e.g. host adapters, video cards, sound cards, printers, scanners, modems, and network interface controllers.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] For example, to show the user something on the screen, an application would make a request to the kernel, which would forward the request to its display driver, which is then responsible for actually plotting the character/pixel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A kernel must maintain a list of available devices.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In plug-and-play systems, a device manager first performs a scan on different peripheral buses, such as Peripheral Component Interconnect (PCI) or Universal Serial Bus (USB), to detect installed devices, then searches for the appropriate drivers.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] As device management is a very OS-specific topic, these drivers are handled differently by each kind of kernel design, but in every case, the kernel has to provide the I/O to allow drivers to physically access their devices through some port or memory location.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Important decisions have to be made when designing the device management system, as in some designs accesses may involve context switches, making the operation very CPU-intensive and easily causing a significant performance overhead.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In computing, a system call is how a process requests a service from an operating system's kernel that it does not normally have permission to run.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] System calls provide the interface between a process and the operating system.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most operations interacting with the system require permissions not available to a user-level process, e.g., I/O performed with a device present on the system, or any form of communication with other processes requires the use of system calls.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A system call is a mechanism that is used by the application program to request a service from the operating system.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] They use a machine-code instruction that causes the processor to change mode.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] An example would be from supervisor mode to protected mode.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is where the operating system performs actions like accessing hardware devices or the memory management unit.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Generally the operating system provides a library that sits between the operating system and normal user programs.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Usually it is a C library such as Glibc or Windows API.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The library handles the low-level details of passing information to the kernel and switching to supervisor mode.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] System calls include close, open, read, wait and write.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] To actually perform useful work, a process must be able to access the services provided by the kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is implemented differently by each kernel, but most provide a C library or an API, which in turn invokes the related kernel functions.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The method of invoking the kernel function varies from kernel to kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] If memory isolation is in use, it is impossible for a user process to call the kernel directly, because that would be a violation of the processor's access control rules.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] An important consideration in the design of a kernel is the support it provides for protection from faults (fault tolerance) and from malicious behaviours (security).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] These two aspects are usually not clearly distinguished, and the adoption of this distinction in the kernel design leads to the rejection of a hierarchical structure for protection.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Support for hierarchical protection domains is typically implemented using CPU modes.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many kernels implement "capabilities", i.e., objects provided to user code that allow limited access to an underlying object managed by the kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A common example is file handling: a file is a representation of information stored on a permanent storage device.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel may be able to perform many different operations, including read, write, delete or execute, but a user-level application may only be permitted to perform some of these operations (e.g., it may only be allowed to read the file).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A common implementation of this is for the kernel to provide an object to the application (typically called a "file handle") that the application may then invoke operations on, the validity of which the kernel checks at the time the operation is requested.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Such a system may be extended to cover all objects that the kernel manages, and indeed to objects provided by other user applications.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] An efficient and simple way to provide hardware support of capabilities is to delegate to the memory management unit (MMU) the responsibility of checking access-rights for every memory access, a mechanism called capability-based addressing.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most commercial computer architectures lack such MMU support for capabilities; the Capability Hardware Enhanced RISC Instructions (CHERI) project is developing capability-based mechanisms for several architectures.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate capabilities using commonly supported hierarchical domains.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In this approach, each protected object must reside in an address space that the application does not have access to; the kernel also maintains a list of capabilities in such memory.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The performance cost of address space switching limits the practicality of this approach in systems with complex interactions between objects, but it is used in current operating systems for objects that are not accessed frequently or that are not expected to perform quickly.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] If the firmware does not support protection mechanisms, it is possible to simulate protection at a higher level, for example by simulating capabilities by manipulating page tables, but there are performance implications.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Lack of hardware support may not be an issue, however, for systems that choose to use language-based protection.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] An important kernel design decision is the choice of the abstraction levels where the security mechanisms and policies should be implemented.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Kernel security mechanisms play a critical role in supporting security at higher levels.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] One approach is to use firmware and kernel support for fault tolerance (see above), and build the security policy for malicious behavior on top of that (adding features such as cryptography mechanisms where necessary), delegating some responsibility to the compiler.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Approaches that delegate enforcement of security policy to the compiler and/or the application level are often called *language-based security*.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The lack of many critical security mechanisms in current mainstream operating systems impedes the implementation of adequate security policies at the application abstraction level.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, a common misconception in computer security is that any security policy can be implemented in an application regardless of kernel support.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] According to Mars Research Group developers, a lack of isolation is one of the main factors undermining kernel security.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] They propose their driver isolation framework for protection, primarily in the Linux kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Typical computer systems today use hardware-enforced rules about what programs are allowed to access what data.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The processor monitors the execution and stops a program that violates a rule, such as a user process that tries to write to kernel memory.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In systems that lack support for capabilities, processes are isolated from each other by using separate address spaces.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Calls from user processes into the kernel are regulated by requiring them to use one of the above-described system call methods.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] An alternative approach is to use language-based protection.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In a language-based protection system, the kernel will only allow code to execute that has been produced by a trusted language compiler.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The language may then be designed such that it is impossible for the programmer to instruct it to do something that will violate a security requirement.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Examples of systems with language-based protection include JX and Microsoft's Singularity.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Edsger Dijkstra proved that from a logical point of view, atomic lock and unlock operations operating on binary semaphores are sufficient primitives to express any functionality of process cooperation.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Nonetheless, this approach is generally held to be lacking in terms of safety and efficiency, whereas a message passing approach is more flexible.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A number of other approaches (either lower- or higher-level) are available as well, with many modern kernels providing support for systems such as shared memory and remote procedure calls.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The idea of a kernel where I/O devices are handled uniformly with other processes, as parallel co-operating processes, was first proposed and implemented by Brinch Hansen (although similar ideas were suggested in 1967).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In Hansen's description of this, the "common" processes are called *internal processes*, while the I/O devices are called *external processes*.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Similar to physical memory, allowing applications direct access to controller ports and registers can cause the controller to malfunction, or system to crash.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] With this, depending on the complexity of the device, some devices can get surprisingly complex to program, and use several different controllers.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Because of this, providing a more abstract interface to manage the device is important.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This interface is normally done by a device driver or hardware abstraction layer.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Frequently, applications will require access to these devices.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel must maintain the list of these devices by querying the system for them in some way.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This can be done through the BIOS, or through one of the various system buses (such as PCI/PCIE, or USB).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Using an example of a video driver, when an application requests an operation on a device, such as displaying a character, the kernel needs to send this request to the current active video driver.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The video driver, in turn, needs to carry out this request.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is an example of inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The above listed tasks and features can be provided in many ways that differ from each other in design and implementation.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The principle of *separation of mechanism and policy* is the substantial difference between the two main philosophies of microkernels and monolithic kernels.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Here a *mechanism* is the support that allows the implementation of many different policies, while a *policy* is a particular "mode of operation".
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Because the mechanism and policy are separated, the policy can be easily changed to, e.g., require the use of a security token.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel instead tends to include many policies, therefore restricting the rest of the system to rely on them.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Computer scientist Per Brinch Hansen argued in favour of separation of mechanism and policy.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The failure to properly fulfill this separation is one of the major causes of the lack of substantial innovation in existing operating systems, a problem common in computer architecture.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic design is induced by the "kernel mode"/"user mode" architectural approach to protection (technically called hierarchical protection domains), which is common in conventional commercial systems; in fact, every module needing protection is therefore preferably included into the kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] While monolithic kernels execute all of their code in the same address space (kernel space), microkernels try to run most of their services in user space, aiming to improve maintainability and modularity of their codebase.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most kernels do not fit exactly into one of these categories, but are rather found in between these two designs.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] More exotic designs such as nanokernels and exokernels are available, but are seldom used for production systems.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The Xen hypervisor, for example, is an exokernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In a monolithic kernel, all OS services are part of the kernel and run in kernel mode, thus also residing in the same memory area.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This approach provides rich and powerful hardware access.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] UNIX developer Ken Thompson stated that "it is in [his] opinion easier to implement a monolithic kernel".
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The main disadvantages of monolithic kernels are the dependencies between system components – a bug in a device driver might crash the entire system, for example – and the fact that large kernels can become very difficult to maintain.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Thompson also stated that "It is also easier for [a monolithic kernel] to turn into a mess in a hurry as it is modified".
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels, which have traditionally been used by Unix-like operating systems, contain all the operating system core functions and the device drivers.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel is one single program that contains all of the code necessary to perform every kernel-related task.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Every part that is to be accessed by a program that cannot be put in a library is in the kernel space, including drivers, schedulers, memory management, file systems, and network stacks.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many system calls are provided to applications, to allow them to access all those services.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel, while initially loaded with subsystems that may not be needed, can be tuned to a point where it is as fast as or faster than one that was specifically designed for the hardware, although more relevant in a general sense.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most work in the monolithic kernel is done via system calls.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] These are interfaces, usually kept in a tabular structure, that access some subsystem within the kernel, such as disk operations.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Essentially, calls are made within programs and a checked copy of the request is passed through the system call.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic Linux kernel can be made extremely small not only because of its ability to dynamically load modules but also because of its ease of customization.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, there are some versions that are small enough to fit together with a large number of utilities and other programs on a single floppy disk and still provide a fully functional operating system (one of the most popular of which is muLinux).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This ability to miniaturize its kernel has also led to a rapid growth in the use of Linux in embedded systems.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels consist of the core functions of the operating system and the device drivers with the ability to load modules at runtime.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] They provide rich and powerful abstractions of the underlying hardware.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] They provide a small set of simple hardware abstractions and use applications called servers to provide more functionality.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This particular approach defines a high-level virtual interface over the hardware, with a set of system calls to implement operating system services such as process management, concurrency and memory management in several modules that run in supervisor mode.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A microkernel that is designed for a specific platform or device is only ever going to have what it needs to operate.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The microkernel approach consists of defining a simple abstraction over the hardware, with a set of primitives or system calls to implement minimal OS services such as memory management, multitasking, and inter-process communication.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other services, including those normally provided by the kernel, such as networking, are implemented in user-space programs, referred to as *servers*.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels are easier to maintain than monolithic kernels, but the large number of system calls and context switches might slow down the system because they typically generate more overhead than plain function calls.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Only parts that really require being in a privileged mode are in kernel space, such as IPC (Inter-Process Communication), a basic scheduler or scheduling primitives, basic memory handling, and basic I/O primitives.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many critical parts are now running in user space, including the complete scheduler, memory handling, file systems, and network stacks.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels were invented as a reaction to traditional "monolithic" kernel design, whereby all system functionality was put in one static program running in a special "system" mode of the processor.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In the microkernel, only the most fundamental of tasks are performed at this level, such as being able to access some (not necessarily all) of the hardware, manage memory and coordinate message passing between the processes.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some systems that use microkernels are QNX and GNU Hurd.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In the case of QNX and GNU Hurd, user sessions can be entire snapshots of the system itself, or "views" as it is referred to.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most microkernels use a message passing system to handle requests from one server to another.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The message passing system generally operates on a port basis with the microkernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] As an example, if a request for more memory is sent, a port is opened with the microkernel and the request sent through.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Once within the microkernel, the steps are similar to system calls.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The rationale was that it would bring modularity in the system architecture, which would entail a cleaner system that is easier to debug or dynamically modify, customizable to users' needs, and higher performing.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels are part of operating systems like GNU Hurd, MINIX, MkLinux, QNX and Redox OS.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Although microkernels are very small by themselves, in combination with all their required auxiliary code they are, in fact, often larger than monolithic kernels.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Advocates of monolithic kernels also point out that the two-tiered structure of microkernel systems, in which most of the operating system does not interact directly with the hardware, creates a not-insignificant cost in terms of system efficiency.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels normally provide only the minimal services such as defining memory address spaces, inter-process communication (IPC) and process management.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other functions, such as running hardware processes, are not handled directly by microkernels.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Proponents of microkernels point out those monolithic kernels have the disadvantage that an error in the kernel can cause the entire system to crash.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] With a microkernel, however, if a kernel process crashes, it is still possible to prevent a crash of the system as a whole by merely restarting the service that caused the error.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other services provided by the kernel such as networking are implemented in user-space programs referred to as *servers*.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Servers allow the operating system to be modified by simply starting and stopping programs.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] For a machine without networking support, for instance, the networking server is not started.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The task of moving in and out of the kernel to move data between the various applications and servers creates overhead that is detrimental to the efficiency of microkernels in comparison with monolithic kernels.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Disadvantages in the microkernel exist, however.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The disadvantages for microkernels are extremely context-based.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] As an example, they work well for small single-purpose (and critical) systems because if not many processes need to run, then the complications of process management are effectively mitigated.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A microkernel allows the implementation of the remaining part of the operating system as programs running in user mode, and the use of different operating systems on top of the same unchanged kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] It is also possible to dynamically switch among operating systems and to have more than one active simultaneously.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] As the computer kernel grows, so grows the size and vulnerability of its trusted computing base, in addition to its memory footprint.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is mitigated to some degree by perfecting a virtual memory system, but not all computer architectures have virtual memory support.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] To reduce the kernel's footprint, extensive editing has to be performed to carefully remove unneeded code, which can be very difficult with non-obvious interdependencies between parts of a kernel with millions of lines of code.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] By the early 1990s, due to the various shortcomings of monolithic kernels versus microkernels, monolithic kernels were considered obsolete by virtually all operating system researchers.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] As a result, the design of Linux as a monolithic kernel rather than a microkernel was the topic of a famous debate between Linus Torvalds and Andrew Tanenbaum.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] There is merit on both sides of the argument presented in the Tanenbaum–Torvalds debate.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels are designed to have all of their code in the same address space (kernel space), which some developers argue is necessary to increase the performance of the system.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some developers also maintain that monolithic systems are extremely efficient if well written.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic model tends to be more efficient through the use of shared kernel memory, rather than the slower IPC system of microkernel designs, which is typically based on message passing.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The performance of microkernels was poor in both the 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Studies that empirically measured the performance of these microkernels did not analyze the reasons of such inefficiency.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The explanations of this data were left to "folklore", with the assumption that they were due to the increased frequency of switches from "kernel-mode" to "user-mode", to the increased frequency of inter-process communication and to the increased frequency of context switches.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, as guessed in 1995, the reasons for the poor performance of microkernels might as well have been: (1) an actual inefficiency of the whole microkernel *approach*, (2) the particular *concepts* implemented in those microkernels, and (3) the particular *implementation* of those concepts.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Therefore it remained to be studied if the solution to build an efficient microkernel was, unlike previous attempts, to apply the correct construction techniques.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Hybrid kernels are used in some commercial operating systems, including most versions of Microsoft Windows to date (NT 3.1, NT 3.5, NT 3.51, NT 4.0, 2000, XP, Vista, 7, 8, 8.1, 10 and 11).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Apple's macOS uses a hybrid kernel called XNU, which is based upon code from OSF/1's Mach kernel (OSFMK 7.3) and FreeBSD's monolithic kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Hybrid kernels are similar to microkernels, except they include some additional code in kernel-space to increase performance.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] These kernels represent a compromise that was implemented by some developers to accommodate the major advantages of both monolithic and microkernels.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels are extensions of microkernels with some properties of monolithic kernels.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Unlike monolithic kernels, these types of kernels are unable to load modules at runtime on their own.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This implies running some services (such as the network stack or the filesystem) in kernel space to reduce the performance overhead of a traditional microkernel, but still running kernel code (such as device drivers) as servers in user space.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many traditionally monolithic kernels support loadable kernel modules.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The most well known of these kernels is the Linux kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The modular kernel essentially can have parts of it that are built into the core kernel binary or binaries that load into memory on demand.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A code-tainted module has the potential to destabilize a running kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] By contrast, it is possible to write a driver for a microkernel in a completely separate memory space and test it before "going" live.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a kernel module is loaded, it accesses the monolithic portion's memory space by adding to it what it needs, therefore opening the doorway to possible pollution.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Modules, generally, communicate with the kernel using a module interface of some sort.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] The interface is generalized (although particular to a given operating system) so it is not always possible to use modules.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often the device drivers may need more flexibility than the module interface affords.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Essentially, it is two system calls and often the safety checks that only have to be done once in the monolithic kernel now may be done twice.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A nanokernel delegates virtually all services – including even the most basic ones like interrupt controllers or the timer – to device drivers to make the kernel memory requirement even smaller than a traditional microkernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Exokernels are a still-experimental approach to operating system design.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] They differ from other types of kernels in limiting their functionality to the protection of and multiplexing of access to the raw hardware, providing no hardware abstractions on top of which to develop applications.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] This separation of hardware protection from hardware management enables application developers to determine how to make the most efficient use of the available hardware for each specific program.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Exokernels in themselves are extremely small.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Nonetheless, they are accompanied by library operating systems (see also unikernel), providing application developers with the functionalities of a conventional operating system.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A major advantage of exokernel-based systems is that they can incorporate multiple library operating systems, each exporting a different API, for example one for high level UI development and one for real-time control.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] A multikernel operating system treats a multi-core machine as a network of independent cores, as if it were a distributed system.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] It does not assume shared memory but rather implements inter-process communications as message passing.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p01] Barrelfish was the first operating system to be described as a multikernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Strictly speaking, an operating system (and thus, a kernel) is not *required* to run a computer.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Programs can be directly loaded and executed on the "bare metal" machine, provided that the authors of those programs are willing to work without any hardware abstraction or operating system support.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Most early computers operated this way during the 1950s and early 1960s, which were reset and reloaded between the execution of different programs.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Eventually, small ancillary programs such as program loaders and debuggers were left in memory between runs, or loaded from ROM.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] As these were developed, they formed the basis of what became early operating system kernels.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] The "bare metal" approach is still used today on some video game consoles and embedded systems, but in general, newer computers use modern operating systems and kernels.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] In 1969, the RC 4000 Multiprogramming System introduced the system design philosophy of a small nucleus "upon which operating systems for different purposes could be built in an orderly manner", what would be called the microkernel approach.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the decade preceding Unix, computers had grown enormously in power – to the point where computer operators were looking for new ways to get people to use their spare time on their machines.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] One of the major developments during this era was time-sharing, whereby a number of users would get small slices of computer time, at a rate at which it appeared they were each connected to their own, slower, machine.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] The development of time-sharing systems led to a number of problems.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] One was that users, particularly at universities where the systems were being developed, wanted to hack the system to get more CPU time.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] For this reason, security and access control became a major focus of the Multics project in 1965.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Another ongoing issue was properly handling computing resources: users spent most of their time staring at the terminal and thinking about what to input instead of actually using the resources of the computer, and a time-sharing system should give the CPU time to an active user during these periods.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Finally, the systems typically offered a memory hierarchy several layers deep, and partitioning this expensive resource led to major developments in virtual memory systems.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] The Commodore Amiga was released in 1985, and was among the first – and certainly most successful – home computers to feature an advanced kernel architecture.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] The AmigaOS kernel's executive component, *exec.library*, uses a microkernel message-passing design, but there are other kernel components, like *graphics.library*, that have direct access to the hardware.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] There is no memory protection, and the kernel is almost always running in user mode.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Only special actions are executed in kernel mode, and user-mode applications can ask the operating system to execute their code in kernel mode.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] During the design phase of Unix, programmers decided to model every high-level device as a file, because they believed the purpose of computation was data transformation.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] For instance, printers were represented as a "file" at a known location – when data was copied to the file, it printed out.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Other systems, to provide a similar functionality, tended to virtualize devices at a lower level – that is, both devices *and* files would be instances of some lower level concept.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Virtualizing the system at the file level allowed users to manipulate the entire system using their existing file management utilities and concepts, dramatically simplifying operation.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] As an extension of the same paradigm, Unix allows programmers to manipulate files using a series of small programs, using the concept of pipes, which allowed users to complete operations in stages, feeding a file through a chain of single-purpose tools.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although the end result was the same, using smaller programs in this way dramatically increased flexibility as well as ease of development and use, allowing the user to modify their workflow by adding or removing a program from the chain.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the Unix model, the *operating system* consists of two parts: first, the huge collection of utility programs that drive most operations; second, the kernel that runs the programs.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Over the years the computing model changed, and Unix's treatment of everything as a file or byte stream no longer was as universally applicable as it was before.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although a terminal could be treated as a file or a byte stream, which is printed to or read from, the same did not seem to be true for a graphical user interface.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Even if network communication can be compared to file access, the low-level packet-oriented architecture dealt with discrete chunks of data and not with whole files.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] As the capability of computers grew, Unix became increasingly cluttered with code.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] It is also because the modularity of the Unix kernel is extensively scalable.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] While kernels might have had 100,000 lines of code in the seventies and eighties, kernels like Linux, of modern Unix successors like GNU, have more than 13 million lines.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Modern Unix-derivatives are generally based on module-loading monolithic kernels.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Examples of this are the Linux kernel in the many distributions of GNU, IBM AIX, as well as the Berkeley Software Distribution variant kernels such as FreeBSD, DragonFly BSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD, and macOS.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apart from these alternatives, amateur developers maintain an active operating system development community, populated by self-written hobby kernels that mostly end up sharing many features with Linux, FreeBSD, DragonflyBSD, OpenBSD, or NetBSD kernels and/or being compatible with them.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apple first launched its classic Mac OS in 1984, bundled with its Macintosh personal computer.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apple moved to a nanokernel design in Mac OS 8.6.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Against this, the modern macOS (originally named Mac OS X) is based on Darwin, which uses a hybrid kernel called XNU, which was created by combining the 4.3BSD kernel and the Mach kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Microsoft Windows was first released in 1985 as an add-on to MS-DOS.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Because of its dependence on another operating system, initial releases of Windows, prior to Windows 95, were considered an operating environment (not to be confused with an operating system).
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] This product line continued to evolve through the 1980s and 1990s, with the Windows 9x series adding 32-bit addressing and pre-emptive multitasking; but ended with the release of Windows Me in 2000.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Microsoft also developed Windows NT, an operating system with a very similar interface, but intended for high-end and business users.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] This line started with the release of Windows NT 3.1 in 1993, and was introduced to general users with the release of Windows XP in October 2001—replacing Windows 9x with a completely different, much more sophisticated operating system.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] This is the line that continues with Windows 11.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] The architecture of Windows NT's kernel is considered a hybrid kernel because the kernel itself contains tasks such as the Window Manager and the IPC Managers, with a client/server layered subsystem model.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] It was designed as a modified microkernel, as the Windows NT kernel was influenced by the Mach microkernel but does not meet all of the criteria of a pure microkernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Supervisory program or supervisor is a computer program, usually part of an operating system, that controls the execution of other routines and regulates work scheduling, input/output operations, error actions, and similar functions and regulates the flow of work in a data processing system.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Historically, this term was essentially associated with IBM's line of mainframe operating systems starting with OS/360.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] In other operating systems, the supervisor is generally called the kernel.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the 1970s, IBM further abstracted the supervisor state from the hardware, resulting in a hypervisor that enabled full virtualization, i.e. the capacity to run multiple operating systems on the same machine totally independent of each other.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Hence the first such system was called *Virtual Machine* or *VM*.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although Mach, developed by Richard Rashid at Carnegie Mellon University, is the best-known general-purpose microkernel, other microkernels have been developed with more specific aims.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] The L4 microkernel family (mainly the L3 and the L4 kernel) was created to demonstrate that microkernels are not necessarily slow.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Newer implementations such as Fiasco and Pistachio are able to run Linux next to other L4 processes in separate address spaces.
[src:xenomai/kernel-operating-system-p02] Additionally, QNX is a microkernel that is principally used in embedded systems, and the open-source software MINIX, while originally created for educational purposes, is now focused on being a highly reliable and self-healing microkernel OS.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:xenomai/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:xenomai/rtai] RTAI consists mainly of two parts: an Adeos-based patch to the Linux kernel which introduces a hardware abstraction layer, and a broad variety of services which make lives of real-time programmers easier.
[src:xenomai/rtai] RTAI versions over 3.0 use an Adeos kernel patch, slightly modified in the x86 architecture case, providing additional abstraction and much lessened dependencies on the "patched" operating system.
[src:xenomai/rtai] Adeos is a kernel patch comprising an Interrupt Pipeline where different operating system domains register interrupt handlers.
[src:xenomai/rtai] This way, RTAI can transparently take over interrupts while leaving the processing of all others to Linux.
[src:xenomai/rtai] Use of Adeos also frees RTAI from patent restrictions caused by RTLinux project.
[src:xenomai/rtai] RTAI-XML is a server component of RTAI, implementing a service-oriented way to design and develop real-time (RT) control applications.
[src:xenomai/rtai] This project was born to fulfill the needs of a university group, mainly focused to have a flexible platform for learning control systems design, allowing the students to test their programs remotely, over the Internet.
[src:xenomai/rtai] The alpha version of RTAI-XML showed the potential impact of the basic idea of a net separation of *hard* and *soft* real-time tasks in the programmation logic.
[src:xenomai/rtai] RTAI-XML consists of a server component waiting for incoming calls on a box where a real-time process, the Target, is running (or ready to).
[src:xenomai/rtai] In other words, RTAI-XML provides a simple way towards remoting of control applications, adding flexibility to the RTAI project, without losing the key features of an open and standard implementation.
[src:xenomai/rtai] The RTAI-XML section of this site presents the details of the implementation.
[src:xenomai/rtai] The general architecture is revised, in order to focus the three key components, the Server, the *Server-Target* interface and the *Server-Host* communication.
[src:xenomai/rtai] The Applications section contains some examples of control systems based on RTAI-XML and the References section contains hints and links for further readings on this topic.
[src:xenomai/xenomai] The Xenomai project was launched in August 2001.
[src:xenomai/xenomai] In 2003, it merged with the Real-Time Application Interface (RTAI) project to produce RTAI/fusion, a real-time free software platform for Linux on Xenomai's abstract real-time operating system (RTOS) core.
[src:xenomai/xenomai] Eventually, the RTAI/fusion effort became independent from RTAI in 2005 as the Xenomai project.
[src:xenomai/xenomai] Xenomai is based on an abstract RTOS core, usable for building any kind of real-time interface, over a nucleus which exports a set of generic RTOS services.
[src:xenomai/xenomai] Any number of RTOS personalities called “skins” can then be built over the nucleus, providing their own specific interface to the applications, by using the services of a single generic core to implement it.
[src:xenomai/xenomai] Many differences exist between Xenomai and RTAI, though both projects share a few ideas and support the RTDM (Real Time Data Monitoring) layer.
[src:xenomai/xenomai] The major differences derive from the goals the projects aim for, and from their respective implementation.
[src:xenomai/xenomai] While RTAI is focused on lowest technically feasible latencies, Xenomai also considers clean extensibility (RTOS skins), portability, and maintainability as very important goals.
[src:xenomai/xenomai] Xenomai's path towards Ingo Molnár's PREEMPT_RT support is another major difference compared to RTAI's objectives.
